Introversion is defined by Merriam-Webster as “the state of or tendency or tendency toward being wholly or predominantly concerned with and interested in one’s own mental life.” Merriam-Webster defines depression as “a mood disorder marked especially by sadness, inactivity, difficulty in thinking and concentration, a significant increase or decrease in appetite and time spent sleeping, feelings of dejection and hopelessness, and sometimes suicidal tendencies.” Is the personality of being introverted related to depression?

Major depressive disorder affects approximately 7.1% of the adult U.S. population, or about 17.3 million Americans over the age of 18. Studies have shown that depression is more common among women, and that it is also on the rise among the millennial population. The challenges of depression on our society has been amplified during the recent COVID-19 pandemic.

The [data](https://openpsychometrics.org/_rawdata/DASS_data_21.02.19.zip) was collected from an online version of the Depression Anxiety Stress Scales (DASS). Due to this, the results are higher average depression levels than the population. Even though the depression levels are determined by the DASS survey through a series of tested questions, the extroversion level is purely self-reported.
The DASS survey scales from 0-42 with higher numbers being more severe.

The data showed a significant level of difference in depression between the people self-reporting as extroverts and the people reporting as not extroverts. Although there is a relation between the two, it is not causal and can have many different explanations such as someone misunderstanding being depressed with being not extroverted. People reporting as extroverts scored an average of 20.96 on depression on the DASS scale, while people reporting as not introverted scored an average of 27.20.
